      </accessrestrict>
      <prefercite id="aspace_d46f83fe1cf2552b6a6101f1e5a55436">
         <head>Preferred Citation</head>
         <p>American Studies Program, Yale University, Speeches Made at the 50th Anniversary Reunion (RU 930). Manuscripts and Archives, Yale University Library.</p>  
      </prefercite>
      <arrangement id="aspace_a6122e38d05517445203c2072a8fbc41">
         <head>Arrangement</head>
         <p>The records are arranged alphabetically by speaker.</p>  
      </arrangement>
      <bioghist id="aspace_747b1b50cd13d67bd2159622f9897026">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>The American Studies Program was established at Yale in 1946, but had its roots an earlier cross-disciplinary program known as History, Arts, and Letters (H.A.L.). A gift from William Robertson Coe in 1950 allowed American Studies to become a large-scale program comprised of undergraduate and graduate courses of study in every aspect of American history.</p>  
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_70b42728737631b6ab10443039327938">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The records consist of correspondence and speeches made at the Yale American Studies Program 50th anniversary reunion held in April 1994. The speeches by alumni, faculty, and administrators document the history of the American Studies at Yale and the personal experiences of individuals in the program. Speakers include former Yale president Howard Lamar and Jean-Christophe Agnew, program chair. The reunion was sponsored by the American Studies Program and the Graduate School.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
